```java
// Good code: Using PreparedStatement to prevent SQL injection
public void getUserById(String userId) {
    String query = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?"; // safer
    PreparedStatement pstmt = null;
    ResultSet rs = null;
    try {
        pstmt = connection.prepareStatement(query);
        pstmt.setString(1, userId); // Set the parameter safely
        rs = pstmt.executeQuery();
        // Process the result set
    } catch (SQLException e) {
        e.printStackTrace();
    } finally {
        // Close resources
    }
}
```

In the first snippet, the code is vulnerable to SQL injection because it directly concatenates user input into the SQL query. In the second snippet, the use of `PreparedStatement` mitigates this risk by safely parameterizing the input.

